    <input class="menu-select-button" id="menu-select--yui_3_10_1_1_1398370805769_119039-6b9bcabe-8400-4543-bc25-d110864fb6a0" type="radio" name="menu-selector-yui_3_10_1_1_1398370805769_119039" checked="checked" onchange="applyActiveStyle('-yui_3_10_1_1_1398370805769_119039-6b9bcabe-8400-4543-bc25-d110864fb6a0')"/ >
    <div class="menu menu--yui_3_10_1_1_1398370805769_119039-6b9bcabe-8400-4543-bc25-d110864fb6a0 ">




      <div class="menu-section">


        <div class="menu-section-header">
          <div class="menu-section-title">Meet some of the participants in the Drop Earrings Not Bombs Project.  These are some of the artisans who create the earrings and who are at the heart of the project.</div>

        </div>


        <div class="menu-items">

            <div class="menu-item">



              <div class="menu-item-title">
                Hiba
              </div>


                <div class="menu-item-description">Hiba is the youngest participant in the Drop Earrings Not Bombs project. She left her home in Aleppo for Istanbul with her family in 2013. She was 13 years old at the time, the second of five siblings. For two years she attended Al-Nokhba, a makeshift school for Syrian refugees. However, now at 16 years of age, the school does not offer any classes at her grade level. Instead, she regularly attends courses at Small Projects Istanbul where she has a new community of friends and learning opportunities. She is interested in becoming an interior designer.</div>






            </div>

            <div class="menu-item">



              <div class="menu-item-title">
                Sawsan
              </div>


                <div class="menu-item-description">Sawsan came to Istanbul two years ago to join her son who made the same journey before her. Sawsan's husband, a plumber, stayed behind in Damascus for financial reasons. She is very eager to work. When the situation in Syria affected her family financially she started working as a caretaker of the elderly. She enjoys participating in Drop Earrings Not Bombs workshops and hopes that the project will take off so she can have more earrings to create.</div>






            </div>

            <div class="menu-item">



              <div class="menu-item-title">
                Farida
              </div>


                <div class="menu-item-description">Farida and her family came to Istanbul from Aleppo six months ago. She is the proud mother of three children, ages 3, 9, and 11. In Syria she worked as a housewife while her husband provided for them as an Arabic teacher. He struggles to find work now. She enjoys working on the earrings, stating that, "it forces her to challenge herself artistically."</div>






            </div>

            <div class="menu-item">



              <div class="menu-item-title">
                Nina
              </div>


                <div class="menu-item-description">Nina was born in Baghdad and lived in Damascus from when she was 4 years old. She relocated to Istanbul with her mother and two sisters this year, at age 17. Her father still resides in Baghdad and supports the family financially. Adjusting to Istanbul and the Turkish language has been difficult for Nina. She expresses herself through her love for heavy metal, always wearing black clothes and metal ornaments, and she meets everyone in the workshop with the kindest smile.</div>






            </div>

            <div class="menu-item">



              <div class="menu-item-title">
                Zeyna, Lin, Qotaiba and Mahmoud
              </div>


                <div class="menu-item-description">Zeyna, Lin, Qotaiba and Mahmoud are all from the same family, made Istanbul their home four years ago. Back in Syria Mahmoud was, among many things, a jeweler, designing his own creations with his wife Zeyna at night and selling them in his shop during the day. When the bombs started to hit the city they lived in, Mahmoud travelled alone to Istanbul where he found work as a tour guide. After securing a home for his family, Mahmoud's parents, wife Zeyna, and their two children came to join him. Eventually so did his 6 brothers and their wives, including Lin and Qotaiba. Most of the brothers were able to earn a decent living in the tourism industry until the terror incident that occurred in January. Now they are very active in the Drop Earrings Not Bombs project, especially Mahmoud who plays an integral role in communicating and coordinating the work with project participants, as well as handling shipping.</div>






            </div>

        </div>

